      <a name="news"></a>
      <div class="row">
        <div class="col-md-12">
          <h2> News </h2>
          <ul>
            <li>September 4, 2025: Soliciting input into failure modes that reflect real-world performance of data agents to inform our benchmark. 
              Submit an issue <a href="https://github.com/ucbepic/data-agent-benchmark-study">here</a>.</li>
            <li>September 3, 2025: DocWrangler won the Best Paper Honorable Mention at UIST, an honor reserved for the top handful of papers. 
              The deployed version has also been used 2700+ times. Congrats Shreya and Bhavya!</li>
            <li>September 1, 2025: As we announced in our AIDB keynote at VLDB, 
              we're kicking off a new research agenda in our lab around redesigning data systems for agents,
              likely the dominant workload for databases in the future, by
              supporting and leveraging their characteristics, including scale, heterogeneity, redundancy, and steerability. 
              New preprint <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2509.00997">here</a>.
            </li>
            <li>August 24, 2025: TWIX, our PDF reverse engineering tool, and BARGAIN, our low-cost LLM processing framework, 
              were accepted to SIGMOD 2026. </li>
            <li>August 20, 2025: Welcome to the group, new PhD students, Shubham Agarwal, and also Ruiying Ma (who was an intern with us last year)!</li>
            <li>August 4, 2025: The police records access project was launched simultaneously via <a href="https://clean.latimes.com/">LA Times</a>, <a href="https://clean.sfchronicle.com/">SF Chronicle</a>, 
              <a href="https://clean.calmatters.org/">CalMatters</a>, and <a href="https://policerecords.kqed.org/">KQED</a>.
            A huge milestone for the project; now anyone anywhere can search through those news sites through over a million pages of PDFs
            from 500+ agencies in California that we have organized and extracted information from. 
            Read articles <a href="https://www.kqed.org/news/12050100/thousands-of-once-secret-police-records-are-now-public-heres-how-you-can-use-them">1</a>, <a href="https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/california-police-records-20797063.php">2</a>, 
            <a href="https://calmatters.org/justice/2025/08/police-misconduct-records-database/">3</a>, <a href="https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2025-08-04/clean-database-launch">4</a>. 
            Article from Berkeley  <a href="https://journalism.berkeley.edu/berkeley-and-stanford-police-database/">here</a>.   </li>
            <li>July 5, 2025: DataScout, our LLM-powered data discovery engine, and DocWrangler, an IDE for semantic data processing, 
              were accepted at UIST 2025 in Busan.</li>
            <li>July 2, 2025: Welcome to Lindsey Wei and Ruiqi Chen who are interning with us this summer!</li>
            <li>July 1, 2025: Gave a keynote at the NOVAS workshop at SIGMOD; 
              slides <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/w1nf5szvx7nyg3ykyppa2/2025-novas-keynote.pdf?rlkey=c0ffcbpa3vb2f9ubt65qw0qhy&e=1&st=vplhjrbc&dl=0">here</a>, 
              and also served on a panel on LLM-meets-databases, 
              slides <a href="https://www.dropbox.com/scl/fi/i7jb2z35vwdb3hfr0wxz8/2025-ai-for-db-panel-aditya.pdf?rlkey=pt2fdljudjkfvhtroxzdb3tig&e=2&st=v3z7vk41&dl=0">here</a>.</li>
            <li>June 5, 2025: Fun to talk about agents at the faculty panel on agents at the Snowflake Dev day.</li>
            <li>June 5, 2025: Excited to <a href="https://www.globenewswire.com/news-release/2025/06/04/3093929/0/en/PromptQL-Partners-with-UC-Berkeley-to-Develop-New-Data-Agent-Benchmark-for-Reliability-of-Enterprise-AI-Agents.html">announce</a>
              our partnership with PromptQL on building a benchmark for data agents.</li>
            <li>May 13, 2025: We released <a href="https://github.com/ucbepic/BARGAIN">BARGAIN</a>, led by Sep Zeighami. 
              The BARGAIN framework gives substantial reduction in LLM costs over prior approaches AND also provides stronger guarantees! </li>
            <li>May 2, 2025: We released TWIX, our data extraction framework for templatized PDF documents, <a href="https://t.co/9lB2J3I7uZ">here</a>, led by Yiming. 
            Blog post <a href="https://t.co/S7So7SETTm">here</a>.</li>
            <li>April 18, 2025: We released a <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.13587">preprint</a> on a new interface, RAGGY, for debugging RAG pipelines.</li>
            <li>April 15, 2025: Grad school admission decisions: undergrad alums Ruiying and Reya got into grad school from a number of top places! Reya will be heading to Columbia, while Ruiying will be returning as a grad student to Berkeley! </li>
            <li>April 15, 2025: We contributed to the once-every-five-years report
              on the future of database research, take a <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.11259">look</a>!</li>
            <li>April 7, 2025: Chroma's Generative Benchmarking <a href="https://research.trychroma.com/generative-benchmarking">approach</a> uses Shreya et al's EvalGen work. </li>
            <li>March 1, 2025: Our <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.14738">paper</a>, led by Reya and Shreya, on a benchmark 
            of assertions for LLM pipelines was accepted to NAACL
            as an oral talk!</li>
            <li>February 24, 2025: Turns out, with LLMs, your data systems can now become more proactive. Read about our new vision paper <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.13016">here</a>.
            <li>January 16, 2025: I co-wrote a <a href="https://wp.sigmod.org/?p=3820">blog post</a> on challenges in data exploration and visual analytics that appeared on the SIGMOD blog.</li>
